`crates/ctx-summarize` is the leaf-up context summarization tool: given
repo-relative source paths, it produces `.ctx` files per file and
`rollup.ctx` files per ancestor directory by driving a pluggable `Agent`
(subprocess wire contract) over prompts loaded from disk, gated by
filesystem/scope/safety checks. Depending on this crate's binary gets you
a CLI with two target-selection modes (`FromCache` off ctx-access's task
cache, or explicit `Paths`) and an `--approve` bypass for oversized scope;
depending on the library gets you `dispatch`/`run`/`run_with_prompts` as
the stable entry points, with everything else swappable for testing.

The crate is a strict layer stack — `Cargo.toml` fixes the package/binary
split and the `../ctx-core` path dependency that must stay in sync with
workspace layout; `src/` enforces cli → runner → {fs, agent, cache, cpath,
error} and owns the one true source-path-to-`.context`-path mapping,
the prompt-loading-not-embedding rule, and the shared `SummError` type
that crosses every module boundary; `tests/` is a single integration file
whose fakes (`FakeFs`, `RecordingAgent`) must track the `Fs`/`Agent` trait
signatures defined in `src/` and whose assertions pin the crate's two
load-bearing behaviors: leaves are always written before rollups, and
`intent.md` is never written by any code path here, only read.

Cross-cutting invariant for anyone editing across `src/` and `tests/`:
every distinct failure mode (path traversal, missing prompt, oversized
unapproved scope, secret-like path) must surface as its own `SummError`
variant, and the integration tests are the single place all of these are
exercised together — a new failure mode added in `src/error.rs` without a
matching case in `tests/summarize.rs` is untested by construction.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.